  "prompt": "What are the penalties for money laundering under federal law?",
  "response": "Under federal law, money laundering can result in significant criminal penalties, including:\n\n1. Potential prison sentences:\n- Up to 20 years in federal prison per offense\n- Maximum of 30 years if the laundering involves proceeds from certain serious crimes\n\n2. Financial penalties:\n- Substantial fines, often up to $500,000 or twice the value of the property involved\n- Potential forfeiture of assets used in or derived from the illegal transactions\n\n3. Additional consequences:\n- Criminal record\n- Potential civil penalties\n- Loss of professional licenses\n- Mandatory restitution\n\nThe specific penalties can vary based on factors like:\n- Amount of money involved\n- Nature of underlying criminal activity\n- Individual's role in the laundering scheme\n- Prior criminal history\n\nProsecution typically occurs through statutes like:\n- 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1956 (money laundering)\n- 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1957 (monetary transactions in criminally derived property)\n\nThese are general guidelines, and actual penalties would be determined by a federal court based on specific case details.",
